<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec32-PropertiesDeterminants" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Properties of Determinants</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In this section, we will see how to compute the determinant of a matrix inverse, which also tells us about the invertibility of a matrix. 
    </p>

    <objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          After this section, students will be able to:
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Apply the multiplicative property of determinants
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            determine whether a matrix is invertible by computing its determinant
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
  </introduction>

  <p>
    The most important theorem about determinants is this one: 
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-DeterminantsProducts">
    <title>Determinants and Products</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Suppose <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n \times n</m> matrices. 
            Then
            <md>
                \det (AB) = \det A \det B
            </md>
            That is, the determinant of the product is the product of the determinants. 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  
  <p>
    And one consequence of this is the following Lemma: 
  </p>

  <lemma xml:id="lem-DeterminantsInverses">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> matrix, then <m>\det A = 0</m> if and only if <m>A</m> has <alert>no</alert> inverse (hence <m>A</m> is not invertible). 
        </p>
    </statement>
  </lemma>

  <example>
    <p>
        We know that
        <md>
            \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp -2 \\ -9 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 5 \amp 0 \\ -9 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp \frac{-2}{5} \\ 0 \amp \frac{7}{5} \end{bmatrix}
        </md>
        We can calculate the determinant of all three matrices and quickly verify that
        <md>
            \begin{vmatrix} 5 \amp -2 \\ -9 \amp 5 \end{vmatrix} = \begin{vmatrix} 5 \amp 0 \\ -9 \amp 1 \end{vmatrix} \begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp \frac{-2}{5} \\ 0 \amp \frac{7}{5} \end{vmatrix}
        </md>
    </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    If we know that <m>A</m> is invertible, then we can use the above theorem to compute the determinant of the inverse of <m>A</m>. 
    Since <m>AA^{-1} = I</m>, we have
    <md>
    <mrow> \det (AA^{-1}) \amp= \det I </mrow>
      <mrow> \implies \qquad \det A \det A^{-1} \amp= 1 </mrow>
        <mrow>\implies \qquad  \det A^{-1} \amp= \frac{1}{\det A} </mrow>
    </md>
    Hence, <m>\det\lp A^{-1} \rp = \dfrac{1}{\det A}</m>
  </p>

  <p>
    The last theorem in this section is about the determinant of a transpose. 
    Long story short, the determinant of a matrix is the same as the determinant of its transpose. 
    That is, 
    <md>
      \det \lp A^T \rp = \det A
    </md>
  </p>

  <worksheet xml:id="ws-sec32">
    <title>Some Exercises for This Section</title>
    
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Richard included some practice problems that cover some main concepts in this section. 
        You don't need to turn it in, but you are highly encouraged to work on this with your classmates. 
        The problems here may end up being in-class practice problems, homework problems, and/or exam problems. 
        Reach out to Richard for help if you get stuck or have any questions. 
      </p>

      <p>
        Only the final answers are included to some of the problems for you to check your result. 
        If you want to check your work, talk to Richard and he is happy to discuss the process with you. 
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>
              Find the determinants in the following exercises by row reduction to echelon form.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        
        <exercise number="3.2.5">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp 5 \amp -4 \\ -1 \amp -4 \amp 5 \\ -2 \amp -8 \amp 7 \end{vmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="3.2.9">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{vmatrix} 1 \amp -1 \amp -3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 5 \amp 4 \\ -1 \amp 0 \amp 5 \amp 3 \\ 3 \amp -3 \amp -2 \amp 3 \end{vmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

        <exercise number="3.2.13">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Combine the methods of row reduction and cofactor expansion to compute the following determinant:
                <me>\begin{vmatrix} 2 \amp 5 \amp 4 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 7 \amp 6 \amp 2 \\ 6 \amp -2 \amp -4 \amp 0 \\ -6 \amp 7 \amp 7 \amp 0 \end{vmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="3.2.17">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Find the determinant of the following matrix, where <m>\begin{vmatrix}a \amp b \amp c\\ d \amp e \amp f\\ g \amp h \amp i\end{vmatrix}=7</m>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix} a+d \amp b+e \amp c+f \\ d \amp e \amp f \\ g \amp h \amp i \end{bmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>
              In the following exercises, use determinants to find out if the matrix is invertible.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise number="3.2.21">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 6 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 9 \amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="3.2.23">
            <statement>
                <me>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 6 \\ 1 \amp -7 \amp -5 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 8 \amp 6 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 7 \amp 5 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</me>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

        <exercise number="3.2.25">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Use determinants to decide if the following set of vectors is linearly independent. 
                <me>\begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ -4 \\ -6 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} -8 \\ 5 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 7 \\ 0 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix}</me>
              </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

    <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
            <p>
              In the following exercises, <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>n \times n</m> matrices. 
              Mark each statement True or False (T/F). Justify each answer.
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise number="3.2.27">
            <statement>
                <p>
                  (T/F) A row replacement operation does not affect the determinant of a matrix.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="3.2.29">
            <statement>
                <p>
                  (T/F) If the columns of <m>A</m> are linearly dependent, then <m>\det A=0</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="3.2.31">
            <statement>
                <p>
                  (T/F) If three row interchanges are made in succession, then the new determinant equals the old determinant.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise number="3.2.33">
            <statement>
                <p>
                  (T/F) <m>\det(A+B) = \det A + \det B</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>
  </worksheet>

</section>